*[other/bootstrap_daemon/src/tox-bootstrapd.c, line 247 at r1](https://reviewable.io:443/reviews/toktok/c-toxcore/296#-KYSF9StAuwDBiEQGPzM:-KYSF9StAuwDBiEQGPzN:blob3f1) ([raw file](https://github.com/toktok/c-toxcore/blob/8f320c8714ba7c5bf742e42d91a95227708f76c0/other/bootstrap_daemon/src/tox-bootstrapd.c#L247)):*
> ```C
>     }
> 
>     DHT *dht = new_DHT(NULL, net, true, true);
> ```

This breaks bootstrap daemon badly.

If you look below, you would see that the daemon has option variable for enabling the LAN discovery, which comes from parsing a configuration file defined by the user, yet you enable it here unconditionally.

Also, the daemon does the LAN discovery on its own, since it wasn't handled by DHT. Does DHT now also do the LAN discovery and it's unnecessary to do it manually?

Here is the code portion from below that I refer to

```C
    if (enable_lan_discovery) {
        LANdiscovery_init(dht);
        write_log(LOG_LEVEL_INFO, "Initialized LAN discovery successfully.\n");
    }
 
    while (1) {
        do_DHT(dht);
 
        if (enable_lan_discovery && is_timeout(last_LANdiscovery, LAN_DISCOVERY_INTERVAL)) {
            send_LANdiscovery(htons_port, dht);
            last_LANdiscovery = unix_time();
        }
        ...
    }
```

